Religion is about believeing...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It's only recently, like within perhaps the last 200 or 300 years that there's ever been a distinction between the two, as the most knowledgeable, or educated, people were also the religious leaders. <br>
<br>
Science simply means Knowledge/Study.  Look up the two words for yourself. You'll see how silly it was for you to say that religion was just about believing in the unknown.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  There were some proto humans and prehumans.. and even even the so calle dmissing links. but modern man is not 30k years old.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Early homo sapiens were around as early as 600,000 years ago. Modern homo sapiens (that's us) showed up around 100,000 years ago.<br>
<br>
The earliest known date of civilization (urban, writing, culture) is c. 3100 BCE. Prior to that, the earliest evidence of domesticated grains (agrarian) was c. 8500 BCE. The significance of mentioning this particular range in time is that around 8500 BCE, humans found themselves with a surplus of food. Once that happens, you don't need all members of your group devoted to hunting/gathering, and can now focus more time on other things not directly related to the actual gathering of food. One of those things could be to focus on matters of the spirit. And that's exactly what they did. Between 8500 BCE and 3100 BCE, enough religious knowledge and behavior had developed, and also wonder of wonders, humans had learned to write, that our earliest evidence of civilization, with written texts, shows a highly religious lifestyle. These people believed that everything they learned came from the gods. Religion and Science were not two different words--they were the same thing.<br>
<br>
In many civilizations, those who gave you knowledge (science) were your religious (faith) leaders and the gods.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   And organized religion as we have it today is not that old either.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't know about you, but I figure once a group of people agree to let one or more of a smaller group of people handle matters of the spirit and other metaphysical pursuits, that's pretty organized. Homo Neanderthalis existed roughly 150,000 to 30,000 years ago, and there is archaelogical evidence of some superstitious or religious belief. And these aren't even us.<br>
<br>
The archaelogical record shows religion &quot;or belief in the unknown&quot; to be pretty darn old. When we went agrarian, is when we got religion organized, but if that's not enough proof for you, I point you to the oldest <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   written</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> evidence of organized religion: Sumeria. That by no means means that's when organized religion started, that's just one civilization that happened to record it, and we happened to find it.<br>
<br>
I suppose that 10,000 years isn't an awfully long time, if you compare it to Evolution in general, so you have a point. But when compared to the very relevant modern homo sapiens timeline, its amazingly old.<br>
<br>
If you think religion is just about believing in the unknown, *that's* been around for a long time, probably not much after we started talking. Organizing that belief system, at the very LATEST (not so long ago) occurred 5,000 years ago.<br>
<br>
I think that's pretty old. And it involves a lot more than just faith in the unknown. <br>
<br>
<br>
